Back in July the Biden administration said it still supports the one China policy and it would seem a risky move to allow this to progress https://news.cgtn.com/news/2021-07-17/How-Biden-s-America-really-sees-Taiwan-11Y8B0nwLeM/index.html Maybe Taiwan should progress to another Lithuania like state rather than the US. Seems unlikely to me - I will expect that the evidence of others will push me lower but I will start here for now According to the one China policy - for the US to have a diplomatic relationship with Taiwan they would have to drop diplomatic relationship with China. Only about 12 small nations have done this. But this could be resolved with just a name change - not diplomatic relationship? EU is pushing for Taiwan economic development treaty (another Q on GJO) but it won't be a "diplomatic relationship"

The potential change from Taipei to Taiwan is guaranteed to raise the ire of Beijing. An indication of their anger was shown when the Taiwanese government announced its new office in Vilnius would be called the “Taiwanese Representative Office in Lithuania. Beijing withdrew its ambassador, demanded the withdrawal of the Lithuanian ambassador form Beijing and limited trade and links. As Lithuania is a member of the EU, this could only effect cultural issues (perhaps). The results of a similar change to Taipei/Taiwan naming of its ‘consulate’ in the US would have the consequence of annoying Beijing but to what advantage? The U.S. commitment to Taiwan has not changed (supplying new weapons etc) and China will be aware of this. Biden and President Xi do talk and this ‘poking of a stick’ would appear to have little value and maintaining a dialog must be a priority, but 2023 is a long way off and the geo-politics can change.
